examples.context:
## for and range
Iterate through an `Iterator` using `for in`. Ranges `a..b` (exclusive end) and `a..=b` (inclusive end) create iterators.

```cairo
fn main() {
    // `n` will take the values: 1, 2, ..., 100
    for n in 1..101_u8 {
        if n % 15 == 0 { println!("fizzbuzz"); }
        else if n % 3 == 0 { println!("fizz"); }
        else if n % 5 == 0 { println!("buzz"); }
        else { println!("{}", n); }
    }
}
```

```cairo
fn main() {
    // `n` will take the values: 1, 2, ..., 100
    for n in 1..= 100_u8 {
        if n % 15 == 0 { println!("fizzbuzz"); }
        else if n % 3 == 0 { println!("fizz"); }
        else if n % 5 == 0 { println!("buzz"); }
        else { println!("{}", n); }
    }
}
```

## Arrays, Spans, and Fixed-Size Arrays
`Array` is a growable, write-once collection. `Span` is an immutable snapshot. `Fixed-Size Array` is an immutable sequence known at compile time.

```cairo
fn main() {
    let mut arr = array![];
    arr.append(1);
    arr.append(2);
    arr.append(3);

    println!("First element of the array: {}", *arr[0]);
    println!("Second element of the array: {}", *arr[1]);
    println!("Number of elements in the array: {}", arr.len());

    let span = arr.span();
    let _ = arr.pop_front();
    println!("First element in span: {}", *span[0]);

    let xs: [u32; 3] = [1, 2, 3];
    let ys: [u32; 3] = [0; 3];
    println!("xs: {:?}", xs);
    println!("ys: {:?}", ys);
    println!("ys first element: {}", *xs.span()[0]);
}
```

## Formatted print
Printing is handled by macros in `core::fmt`: `format!`, `print!`, `println!`. Cairo checks formatting correctness at compile time.

- `{}`: automatically replaced with stringified arguments.
- `{0}`: positional arguments.
- `{:x}`: different formatting (e.g., hexadecimal).
- `fmt::Debug`: uses `{:?}` for debugging.
- `fmt::Display`: uses `{}` for user-friendly output.

```cairo
struct Structure { inner: i32, }

fn main() {
    println!("{} days", 31);
    let alice: ByteArray = "Alice";
    let bob: ByteArray = "Bob";
    println!("{0}, this is {1}. {1}, this is {0}", alice, bob);
    println!("Base 10:               {}", 69420);
    println!("Base 16 (hexadecimal): {:x}", 69420);
    let bond: ByteArray = "Bond";
    println!("My name is {0}, {1} {0}", bond, "James"); // Fixed: Added missing argument
    // println!("This struct `{}` won't print...", Structure(3)); // Will not compile without fmt::Display
}
```

## Pulling `Result`s out of `Option`s
`Option` and `Result` can be nested. `map` can be used to transform values within `Option`.

```cairo
#[derive(Drop, Debug)]
struct ParseError { message: ByteArray, }

fn parse_ascii_digit(value: @ByteArray) -> Result<u32, ParseError> {
    if value.len() != 1 { Result::Err(ParseError { message: "Expected a single character" }) }
    else { let byte = value[0]; if byte >= '0' && byte <= '9' { Result::Ok((byte - '0').into()) } else { Result::Err(ParseError { message: "Character is not a digit" }) } }
}

fn double_first(arr: Array<ByteArray>) -> Option<Result<u32, ParseError>> {
    arr.get(0).map(|first| { parse_ascii_digit(first.unbox()).map(|n| 2 * n) })
}

fn main() {
    let numbers = array!["4", "9", "1"];
    let empty = array![];
    let strings = array!["t", "9", "1"];

    println!("The first doubled is {:?}", double_first(numbers));
    println!("The first doubled is {:?}", double_first(empty));
    println!("The first doubled is {:?}", double_first(strings));
}
```

## `map` for `Result`
`Result<T, E>` represents success (`Ok(T)`) or failure (`Err(E)`). `map`, `and_then` and other combinators are available for `Result`.

```cairo
#[derive(Drop)]
struct ParseError { message: ByteArray, }

fn parse_ascii_digit(value: ByteArray) -> Result<u32, ParseError> {
    if value.len() != 1 { Result::Err(ParseError { message: "Expected a single character" }) }
    else { let byte = value[0]; if byte >= '0' && byte <= '9' { Result::Ok((byte - '0').into()) } else { Result::Err(ParseError { message: "Character is not a digit" }) } }
}

// Using match
fn multiply_match(first_number: ByteArray, second_number: ByteArray) -> Result<u32, ParseError> {
    match parse_ascii_digit(first_number) {
        Result::Ok(first_number) => {
            match parse_ascii_digit(second_number) {
                Result::Ok(second_number) => { Result::Ok(first_number * second_number) },
                Result::Err(e) => Result::Err(e),
            }
        },
        Result::Err(e) => Result::Err(e),
    }
}

// Using and_then
fn multiply(first_number: ByteArray, second_number: ByteArray) -> Result<u32, ParseError> {
    parse_ascii_digit(first_number)
        .and_then(|first_number| { parse_ascii_digit(second_number).map(|second_number| first_number * second_number) })
}

fn print(result: Result<u32, ParseError>) {
    match result {
        Result::Ok(n) => println!("n is {}", n),
        Result::Err(e) => println!("Error: {}", e.message),
    }
}

fn main() {
    let twenty = multiply("4", "5");
    print(twenty);
    let tt = multiply("t", "2");
    print(tt);
}
```

## Destructuring
`match` blocks can destructure enums and structs. Structs can also be destructured with `let` bindings.

## Attributes
Metadata applied to modules, crates, or items, e.g., `#[derive(Debug)]`.

```cairo
#[derive(Debug)]
struct Rectangle { width: u32, height: u32, }
```

## `TryInto` for Fallible Conversions
The `TryInto` trait is used for conversions that might fail, returning `Option<T>`.

```cairo
#[derive(Copy, Drop, Debug)]
struct EvenNumber { value: u32, }

impl U32IntoEvenNumber of TryInto<u32, EvenNumber> {
    fn try_into(self: u32) -> Option<EvenNumber> {
        if self % 2 == 0 { Option::Some(EvenNumber { value: self }) } else { Option::None }
    }
}

fn main() {
    let even: Option<EvenNumber> = 8_u32.try_into();
    println!("{:?}", even);
    let odd: Option<EvenNumber> = 5_u32.try_into();
    println!("{:?}", odd);
}
```

## Retaining Ownership
- **Snapshots (`@T`)**: Immutable view into memory cells.
- **References (`ref T`)**: Syntactic sugar for mutable ownership transfer.

## `Result`
`Result<T, E>` describes possible error (`Err(E)`) or success (`Ok(T)`).

```cairo
#[derive(Drop)]
struct ParseIntError { message: ByteArray, }

fn char_to_number(c: ByteArray) -> Result<u8, ParseIntError> {
    if c.len() != 1 { return Result::Err(ParseIntError { message: "Expected a single character" }); }
    let byte = c[0];
    Result::Ok(byte)
}

fn main() {
    let result = char_to_number("a");
    match result {
        Result::Ok(number) => println!("Number: 0x{:x}", number),
        Result::Err(error) => println!("Error: {}", error.message),
    }
    let result = char_to_number("ab");
    match result {
        Result::Ok(number) => println!("Number: 0x{:x}", number),
        Result::Err(error) => println!("Error: {}", error.message),
    }
}
```

## Returning from loops
A `loop` can return a value using `break`.

```cairo
fn main() {
    let mut counter = 0;
    let result = loop {
        counter += 1;
        if counter == 10 { break counter * 2; }
    };
    assert!(result == 20);
}
```

## while
The `while` keyword runs a loop while a condition is true.

```cairo
fn main() {
    let mut n = 1_u8;
    while n < 101 {
        if n % 15 == 0 { println!("fizzbuzz"); }
        else if n % 3 == 0 { println!("fizz"); }
        else if n % 5 == 0 { println!("buzz"); }
        else { println!("{}", n); }
        n += 1;
    }
}
```

## ByteArrays
`ByteArray` is the main string type in Cairo, optimized for sequences of bytes. Can be concatenated with `+`.

```cairo
fn main() {
    let pangram: ByteArray = "the quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog";
    println!("Pangram: {}", pangram);

    let mut chars = pangram.clone().into_iter();
    for c in chars {
        println!("ASCII: 0x{:x}", c);
    }

    let alice: ByteArray = "I like dogs";
    let bob: ByteArray = "I like " + "cats";
    println!("Alice says: {}", alice);
    println!("Bob says: {}", bob);
}
```

## Testcase: List
Implementing `fmt::Display` for custom types, using `write!` and the `?` operator for error propagation.

```cairo
use core::fmt;

#[derive(Drop)]
struct List { inner: Array<i32>, }

impl ListDisplay of fmt::Display<List> {
    fn fmt(self: @List, ref f: fmt::Formatter) -> Result<(), fmt::Error> {
        let array_span = self.inner.span();
        write!(f, "[")?;
        let mut count = 0;
        loop {
            if count >= array_span.len() { break Ok(()); }
            if count != 0 { match write!(f, ", ") { Ok(_) => {}, Err(e) => { break Err(e); }, } }
            match write!(f, "{}", *array_span[count]) { Ok(_) => {}, Err(e) => { break Err(e); }, }
            count += 1;
        }?;
        write!(f, "]")
    }
}

fn main() {
    let mut arr = ArrayTrait::new();
    arr.append(1);
    arr.append(2);
    arr.append(3);
    let v = List { inner: arr };
    println!("{}", v);
}
```

## Structures
Structures (`struct`s) define custom data types with named fields. They can be instantiated, their fields accessed, and destructured.

```cairo
#[derive(Drop, Debug)]
struct Person { name: ByteArray, age: u8, }

#[derive(Drop, Debug)]
struct Unit {}

#[derive(Drop)]
struct Point { x: u32, y: u32, }

#[derive(Drop)]
struct Rectangle { top_left: Point, bottom_right: Point, }

fn main() {
    let name: ByteArray = "Peter";
    let age = 27;
    let peter = Person { name, age };
    println!("{:?}", peter);

    let point: Point = Point { x: 5, y: 0 };
    let another_point: Point = Point { x: 10, y: 0 };
    println!("point coordinates: ({}, {})", point.x, point.y);

    let bottom_right = Point { x: 10, ..another_point };
    println!("second point: ({}, {})", bottom_right.x, bottom_right.y);

    let Point { x: left_edge, y: top_edge } = point;
    let _rectangle = Rectangle { top_left: Point { x: left_edge, y: top_edge }, bottom_right: bottom_right, };
    let _unit = Unit {};
}
```

## structs (destructuring)
Structs can be destructured directly or nested.

```cairo
#[derive(Copy, Drop)]
struct Foo { x: (u32, u32), y: u32, }

#[derive(Drop)]
struct Bar { foo: Foo, }

fn main() {
    let _foo = Foo { x: (1, 2), y: 3 };
    let faa = Foo { x: (1, 2), y: 3 };

    let Foo { x: x0, y: y0 } = faa;
    println!("Outside: x0 = {x0:?}, y0 = {y0}");

    let bar = Bar { foo: faa };
    let Bar { foo: Foo { x: nested_x, y: nested_y } } = bar;
    println!("Nested: nested_x = {nested_x:?}, nested_y = {nested_y:?}");
}
```

